					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/eskobar" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1173523); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1173523&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164600" alt="Eskobar" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1173523)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/eskobar" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1173523); return false;" >Eskobar</a></span> <span class="odate time_1323924485 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Dec 2011 04:48</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1328613">
									

<p>I read a book (<em>The Ghost Map</em>, it's really good, if you're wondering) about a cholera epidemic in London in the 1850s. That book describes the impact that miasma had on public containment efforts of disease, namely keeping people from focusing on contaminated water and making them be obsessed with &quot;oh god does it smell bad?&quot; So based on that, miasma was still taken seriously in public.</p>
<p>That said, there is an argument that the ASCI (for all of its many, many, MANY flaws) would still have been more scientifically advanced than the rest of the country, so they may have been less into the theory than I'm describing.</p>
<p>The way I see it (headcanonically), the Foundation would have needed vast amounts of wealth to operate in any time. That means its central membership would be upper-class white men. This is, in a realistic sense, the sort of things upper-class white 19th century men believed in, by and large.</p>

							</div>

								
					
