<p>For the first note: The way I see it, the ASCI would have seen itself being above the political strife, officially. Those areas that allowed slavery, the ASCI owned and used them there (many of those states being Unionist during the war); where they didn't own slaves, they recognized the benefits of slavery for themselves. (Fun fact, that was also a large part of Northern Democratic support among lower-class laborers between 1828 and 1850 or so.) They didn't back the North or the South, but their official line would have been for the bigger dog, with the willingness to switch sides whenever convenient.</p>
<p>I wrote &quot;recent&quot; meaning &quot;recently begun&quot;, but I see the confusion. And &quot;The War of Northern Aggression&quot; makes my eyes bleed, so no, I'll not be using that one.</p>

