				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/miguel-pimentel" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1371174); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1371174&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164600" alt="Miguel Pimentel" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1371174)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/miguel-pimentel" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1371174); return false;" >Miguel Pimentel</a></span> <span class="odate time_1353800215 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 Nov 2012 23:36</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1626577">
									

<p>I understand this sentiment. It's heartfelt and a sincere way of showing how you feel. That said, as a person of color (Hispanic, actually) I honestly feel that a fictional article where a fictional entity expresses disgust over terrible things that another fictional entity has been doing isn't really all that bad. My understanding of White Privilege is that it's simply accepting the overriding culture that holds white males in higher regard than anyone else. If the article were garbage, you wouldn't be praising yourself by saying so. If it were great, you wouldn't be making amends by upvoting it.</p>
<p>It's seems to me as one of those situations where color can be put aside with regards to voting. Then again, I tend to act on a &quot;good faith&quot; approach to the whole thing. I see no reason to play the &quot;race card&quot; unless it's obvious that race is what it's all about.</p>
<p>So, in a long-winded way I'm saying upvote or downvote not on the color of the Drapetomatic Class but on the content of the article's character.</p>

							</div>

								
					
